   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.1913_1.jpg"/>

            <opener>


               <address>
                  <addrLine>30, Hardy Road</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Blackheath</addrLine>

               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1912-11-28">November 28. 1912.</date>
               </dateline>

               <salute> Dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hardy,</salute>

            </opener>

            <p>It was indeed a shock to me to receive your letter this morning, for recent letters
               from <persName ref="#ps:EmmaHardy">Emma</persName> had not for a moment led us to
               suspect <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.1913_2.jpg"/> that she was not in good health. For
               me it is the snapping of another link with the past and I am in full sympathy with
               you.</p>

            <p>I much regret that I am entirely unfit to be with you on Saturday when I should have
               liked to <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.1913_3.jpg"/> represent the Gifford side. I am
               unable to walk &amp; rarely leave my easy chair.</p>

            <p>My daughter <persName ref="#ps:LeonieGifford"><unclear>Leonie</unclear></persName>
               asks me to say that she would be more than ready to come to you at once if she could
               be of real use in the absence of such help as only a woman can give. She &amp; <pb
                  n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.1913_4.jpg"/> my sister send sympathetic messages.</p>


            <closer>


               <salute>Yours very sincerely</salute>
               <signed>C. E. Gifford</signed>
            </closer>



         </div>
      </body>
